                   <CENTER></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uevantineessidel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Evantine Essidel</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer<BR>Peaceful PvPer</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/14/02 5:51:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1133.topic&index=40>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: God and Religion (OT)</span><hr size=1> For me, atheism is a scary thought. No matter how low my spiritual self has sunk, I've always believed that there was <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> something</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> other than a forever dark empty unconsious undreaming abyss after you die.<br>
<br>
Aurianne's right, too, you know. Science is founded on being able to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> prove</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> things, and they can prove their idea's all the way back to the creation of life, but for the life of them they can't explain how that first organism came into being. In a way, science has become a sort of religion. Some people believe that eventually, it will be able to explain everything.<br>
<br>
And LaSorcier had a good point. I got my car stuck in a ditch (long story), and was trying to dig it out. After about an hour, I was desperate, and just started praying. I felt better. I know it's weird, but I just felt a LOT better after I had got it off my back. Not so alone. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uoglzogl.showPublicProfile?language=EN>oglzogl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/14/02 6:42:48 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1133.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: God and Religion (OT)</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Atheists do vehemently push the separation of Church from the masses, though. They take *great* offense when Religion is put into school, and yet the religious, who vastly outnumber the atheists, don't really complain when it's removed. Those who are vocal tend to be the ones who fear something.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This sentence really bothers me. From my understanding it is not only the atheists who oppose the idea of prayer in school. The problem was that it was the Christian God who was being prayed to and other religions were not being properly represented as well.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Do we need to distinguish between God and Gravity?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This sentence reinforces my idea that religion really came about because people were trying to explain forces of nature that they couldn't understand. Putting a human face on that force, or at least giving that force a name, and worsipping it does not mean that the force has any sort of conciousness and will recognize the act of worship.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Thanks Oglzogl for the suggestion re Mark Twain's Mysterious Stranger. Despite a disappointing ending, it was a gripping read with some profound questions/hypotheticals.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
