Can you tell me how God came to be? For me, it is the same dilemma. Something from nothing. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/uyalazar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Yalazar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/14/02 6:50:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1133.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: God and Religion (OT)</span><hr size=1> I think I have to go with oglzogl on this one. My reason is that teh Universe is about to become aware (and with about I mean in a couple of billion years....). Thought: Our brains are composed of LOTS of cells, internet is composed of LOTS of 'brains' (humans interacting). Now we just assume that there is other civilizations out there whom also has some technology for communication over long distances. As we grov more advanced we will begin to communicate with these people and thereby expanding the 'collective brain' until it encompasses a arther big part of the Universe. Since every cell in your head is quite unaware of the brain, and the brain (from a purely 'organic' point of view) is unawareof the internet, so will we be unaware of the consciousness of the Universe. Who know? Maybe it is already aware?<br>
<br>
