Personally I wouldn't mind a study in Comparitive religion, meaning take As many of the currently practiced religions in the world (hell take the beliefs of the Romans, and Greeks too) and teach as a science the differences and similarities to each other.  Teaching about religion and teaching religion are two entirely different subjects.  That I think is the main complaint with &quot;Prayer in the Schools&quot; it is seen as proselytizing. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub23.ezboard.com/ugrindel.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Grindel</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Sorcerer</span><br> <font color=#ffffff>(5/14/02 7:11:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub23.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1133.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.cox.net/grindel/elminster.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: God and Religion (OT)</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Do we need to distinguish between God and Gravity?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Bah, the Creator is gravity, or more aptly gravity is a reflection of the Creator that we can sense.  But then again so is the pixel in the letter 'i' in this sentence.<br>
<br>
Slightly changing topics, science and theology combine easily for me.  I have no problem with the notion that a logical Creator would create a universe based on specific rules (many of which we don't have clue #1 about).  God creates Man, but uses several million years of evolution to do it.  In another several million years, provided we haven't exterminated ourselves first (or maybe BECAUSE we have) God will have created some other species.  Hopefully a more enlightened one than this one.  We are arrogant to believe we are the acme of creation.  Or that we have the tools to see more than the tiniest sliver of what is around us.  We can directly sense a small sliver of what, four dimensions around us?  We are blind.<br>
<br>
